title: Organochlorine pesticides, PCBs, dioxins and metals in post-term peregrine falcon (Falco peregrinus) eggs from the mid-Atlantic states: New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, and Virginia: 1993-1999
name: organochlorine-pesticides-pcbs-dioxins-and-metals-in-post-term-peregrine-falcon-falco-1993
notes: For Peregrine falcons represented by post-term egg residues in this study, eggshell thicknesses (n = 93) were not at levels known to be critical for effects to next success. There was no statistically significant effect of contaminants on next success (n, clutches =73). DDE remained negatively correlated with thickness. Residues of persistent organochlorines, PCBs and metals were detected in these post-term eggs; some residues approach critical levels for effects to birds. Enacting a sampling plan of the breeding population for the Mid-Western/Northeastern Recovery Region, as described in the Monitoring Plan for the American Peregrine Falcon (USFWS 2003), is advisable. Promoting peregrine falcon nesting in the historic inland habitat in the coastal states is advisable as the coastal nesters appear to bear higher contaminant burdens than those peregrine falcons that forage inland or on more resident prey populations. The coastal nesting peregrines may be accumulating contaminants at higher levels than inland nesting birds due to the somewhat more migrant coastal prey base that may be exposed to bioaccumulative contaminants in many locations. Implementing a randomized egg sampling regime, in accordance with provisions in the Monitoring Plan, would encompass the entire recovery region population and include greater representation from peregrines nesting in more historic habitat. Comprehensive records on number of eggs laid, hatchlings and fledglings at banding would facilitate a more detailed analysis of contaminant effects on productivity as number of nestlings, rather than as successful (>1 chicks at banding) or unsuccessful (0 chicks at banding) nesting. Tracking banded female productivity over a number of years, analyzing eggs on a periodic basis, and tracking winter migration routes and areas of females, although many peregrines falcons in this region are non-migratory, would also allow examination of contaminant trends over time and perhaps discern effects due to foraging and environmental factors.
